# Frontmatter Standards

DocForge project documents use a consistent YAML frontmatter format. This aligns with the docforge-drafter skill and the artefact hierarchy.

## Required Fields

All project documents in `docs/` must include:

- **title**: Document title (required)
- **project**: `DocForge`
- **status**: One of `stub`, `draft`, `approved`, or `template` (for templates only)
- **version**: Semantic version (e.g. `0.1`)
- **created**: Creation date in **YYYY-MM-DD** (ISO format for machine readability)

## Optional Fields

- **updated**: Last update date (YYYY-MM-DD)
- **author**: Author name if known
- **depends_on**: List of upstream document paths (e.g. `docs/strategic/solution-concept.md`) â€” used when the doc is derived from others

## Standard Frontmatter Block

```yaml
---
title: [Document Title]
project: DocForge
status: draft
version: 0.1
created: YYYY-MM-DD
author: [if known]
depends_on:
  - docs/path/to/upstream.md
---
```

## Status Values

- **stub**: Scaffold only; content not yet written.
- **draft**: Content in progress; not yet approved.
- **approved**: Reviewed and accepted.
- **template**: Template file (e.g. ADR-0000); do not use for normal docs.

## Link Standards

Internal links in the body use relative paths and standard Markdown: `[Link Text](path/to/file.md)`. See the markdown-links rule. The `depends_on` field is for upstream dependency traceability, not a replacement for in-document links.

## Governance Documents (RAIDD)

RAIDD and similar governance docs use the same frontmatter. They do not require a `type` field; risks, assumptions, issues, dependencies, and decisions are structured in the document body (tables with IDs), not in frontmatter.
